V{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\u000a{{multiple issues|\u000a{{cleanup rewrite|date=October 2010}}\u000a{{BLP sources|date=January 2011}}\u000a}}\u000a\u000a{{Infobox person\u000a|name=\u000a|birth_date={{birth date and age|1930|5|27}}\u000a|birth_place=[[Bottineau, North Dakota]], US\u000a|death_date=\u000a|death_place=\u000a|occupation=Writer, professor\u000a}}\u000a\u000a'''Ronald Paulson''' (born May 27, 1930 in [[Bottineau, North Dakota]]), is an American professor of English, a specialist in English 18th-century art and culture, and English [[Painting|artist]] [[William Hogarth]].<ref name=Edwards>{{cite news|title=Hogarth; His Life, Art and Times. By Ronald Paulson. Illustrated. Vol. I, 558 pp. Vol. II, 557 pp. New Haven: Yale University Press. Hogarth|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40F16F63D5A137A93C0A9178AD85F468785F9|accessdate=January 18, 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 2, 1972|first= Thomas R. |last=Edwards }}</ref>\u000a\u000a== Education ==\u000a\u000aPaulson earned a [[Bachelor of Arts degree]] from [[Yale University]] in 1952, where he was an editorial associate of campus humor magazine ''[[The Yale Record]]''.<ref>''The Yale Record''. New Haven: Yale Record. February, 1951. p. 3.</ref> He earned his [[doctorate degree]] from Yale in 1958.\u000a\u000a== Academic career ==\u000aPaulson has taught and held various administrative positions at several universities in the United States, including the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]] from 1959 to 1963 and [[Rice University]] from 1963 to 1967. He was the Chairman of the [[Johns Hopkins University]] English Department from 1967 to 1975. From 1975 to 1984 he was a professor at Yale University and served as the Director of Graduate Studies in the English Department from 1976 to 1983 and the Director of the British Studies Program from 1976 to 1984.<ref name=JHU>{{cite web |url=http://english.jhu.edu/bios/ronald-paulson/ |title=Ronald Paulson \u2013 English Department \u2013 Johns Hopkins University |publisher=english.jhu.edu |accessdate=2011-01-18 }}</ref>\u000a\u000aPaulson returned to Johns Hopkins University in 1984, serving as the Department Chairman from 1985 to 1991.<ref name= JHU />\u000a\u000aHe has been a member of the editorial board of the [[academic journal]] ''[[ELH|ELH: English Literary History]]'' and was senior editor from 1985 to 2004; he served on the editorial boards of the journals ''[[Studies in English Literature]]''; PMLA; ''[[Eighteenth-Century Studies]]''; and the Johns Hopkins University Press.<ref name= JHU />\u000a\u000a== Honors and recognitions ==\u000aPaulson was the Andrew W. Mellon Professor of the Humanities at Johns Hopkins University from 1973 to 1975 and has been the Mayer Professor of Humanities since 1985. He was a member of the Academic and Advisory Committees and Governing Board of the [[Yale Center for British Art]] and the Paul Mellon Centre for British Art in London from 1975 to 1984. He has also been a [[Guggenheim Fellowship|Guggenheim Fellow]] (1965\u201366, 1986\u201387), an NEH Senior Fellow (1977\u201378), and a fellow of the [[Rockefeller Foundation]] (1978, 1987).<ref name=JHU />\u000a\u000aIn 1988, Paulson traveled with several [[humorists]] from the United States to the [[Soviet Union]] as part of a cultural exchange.<ref>{{Citation  | last= New York Times Service | title = Laugh Exchange: Humorists take humor to Soviet Union | newspaper = Milwaukee Journal  | page = G1| date = February 16, 1988  | url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1CoqAAAAIBAJ  | accessdate = January 18, 2011 }}</ref>\u000a\u000a== Books ==\u000a* ''Theme and Structure in Swift's 'Tale of a Tub'' (1960)\u000a* ''Hogarth's Graphic Works'' (1965)\u000a* ''The Fictions of Satire'' (1967)\u000a* ''Satire and the Novel in Eighteenth-Century England'' (1967)\u000a* ''Hogarth: His Life, Art, and Times'' (1971)<ref name=Edwards />\u000a* ''Rowlandson: A New Interpretation'' (1972)\u000a* ''Emblem and Expression: Meaning in English Art of the Eighteenth Century'' (1975)\u000a* ''The Art of Hogarth'' (1975)\u000a* ''Popular and Polite Art in the Age of Hogarth and Fielding'' (1979)\u000a* ''Literary Landscape: Turner and Constable'' (1982)\u000a* ''Representations of Revolution (1789\u20131820)'' (1983)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/02/books/books-of-the-times-205150.html |title=Books of the Times |newspaper =The New York Times|first=Anatole |last= Broyard  |date=June 2, 1983|accessdate=2011-01-18 }}</ref>\u000a* ''Book and Painting: Shakespeare, Milton, and the Bible'' (1983)\u000a* ''Breaking and Remaking: Aesthetic Practice in England, 1700\u20131820'' (1989)\u000a* ''Hogarth's Graphic Works'' (rewritten and reset) (1989)\u000a* ''Figure & Abstraction in Contemporary Painting'' (1990)\u000a* ''Hogarth'', Vols. 1\u20133 (1991\u201393)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/1993/may/27/the-genius-of-gin-lane/ |title=The Genius of Gin Lane |first=Richard |last=Dorment |newspaper= The New York Review of Books |publisher=The New York Times|date=May 27, 1993 |accessdate=2011-01-18 }}</ref>\u000a* ''The Beautiful, Novel, and Strange: Aesthetics and Heterodoxy'' (1997)\u000a* ''The Analysis of Beauty'' (editor) (1997)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/1997/dec/18/the-pleasures-of-reading-hogarth/ |title=The Pleasures of Reading Hogarth|first= P.N. |last=Furbank |newspaper= The New York Review of Books |publisher=The New York Times |date= December 18, 1997|accessdate=2011-01-18 }}</ref>\u000a* ''Don Quixote in England: The Aesthetics of Laughter'' (1998)<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.h-net.org/~cervantes/csa/artics99/gorfkle.htm |title=Review of Ronald Paulson's Don Quixote in England: The Aesthetics of Laughter|first= Laura J. |last=Gorfkle |journal=Cervantes: Bulletin of the Cervantes Society of America |volume=19|issue=1|year= 1999|pages=145\u2013149 |accessdate=2011-01-18|publisher= he Cervantes Society of America}}</ref>\u000a* ''The Life of Henry Fielding'' (2000)\u000a* ''Hogarth's Harlot:  Sacred Parody in Enlightenment England''  (2003)\u000a* ''Sin and Evil:  Moral VAlues in Literature''  (2006)\u000a* ''The Art of Riot in England and America''   (2010)\u000a\u000a== References ==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Paulson, Ronald}}\u000a[[Category:1930 births]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:People from Bottineau County, North Dakota]]\u000a[[Category:American academics of English literature]]\u000a[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Rice University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Johns Hopkins University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Yale University faculty]]
